    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-27T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-27T09:00:00-05:00" n="477"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d477">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.91261/2–2746: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-27T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >February 27, 1946—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 27—1:32 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>566. <gloss target="#t_AP1">AP</gloss> correspondent Gilmore<note n="46"
                        xml:id="d477fn46">Eddy Gilmore, Chief of the Moscow Bureau of the Associated
                        Press.</note> tells us that correspondents were yesterday informed by
                    Foreign Office Press <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> that it will no
                    longer handle censorship but will devote itself to “assisting” correspondents.
                    Correspondents will continue to be accredited by Press <gloss target="#t_Dept1"
                        >Dept</gloss>. Beginning March 1 news despatches are to be handed in to post
                    office at which point correspondents will lose contact with their stories.</p>
                <p>Whole matter was presented by Press <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> to
                    correspondents in typical atmosphere of mystery. Gilmore has learned, however,
                    that censorship is in hands of Chief Administration of Literary and Publishing
                    Affairs. This organization exerts internal Soviet censorship. Gilmore feels it
                    is still too early to tell how new system will work but he has misgivings.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
